^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Interesting hand. First let's discuss Bonnie's bid. It turns out, although 2C is a valid DONT bid, Bergen recommends that with 6-4 hands, you treat it as a single suited hand. In fact, not vul, I would recommend Bonnie bid 3D over 1N. But vul, double is what Bergen would recommend, because a 6-card suit plays well over more holdings by pard. |
PG| ***** 108 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|In fact, even on this hand, the 6-2 fit is better than the 4-4 fit. It is because, especially with an 8-card fit, longer trumps in one hand gives you more protection. Bonnie will be having to ruff hearts, and with 6 diamonds, she has more trumps to ruff with. |
PG| ***** 109 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So you may have heard that 4-4 fits are better than 5-3 or 6-2 fits. On some hands, it is true that you will take an extra trick or two in a 4-4 fit, because you can throw losers on the 5 or 6 card suit.|
PG| ***** 110 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|But, it is almost always safer to play with longer trumps in 1 hand when you have an 8 card fit. One way to think about this is you would rather have an 8-0 fit than 4-4. 8-0 has to be safer. That is the same idea, if less extreme, between 6-2 and 4-4.|
